// Regression: `yield <binding>` inside a loop body. A bare `yield v` (where `v`
// is a loop capture) returns a *borrowed* stack reference, not a freshly pushed
// temporary. `yield` must not pop it — doing so corrupted the frame and, since
// the loop body is compiled once and re-run, underflowed the compiler's
// per-iteration ref accounting (an `integer overflow` panic at compile time).
// This covers the live-stream (`for (&0)`) form; the counted array/range forms
// hit the same bug and are exercised by the unit/CLI suites.

fn Void produce() Int {
    yield 10
    yield 20
    yield 30
}

fn Int passthrough() Int {
    for (&0) |v| {
        yield v
    }
}

produce | passthrough
